The people of Macedonia voted on Sunday on whether their country's name should be changed to 'the Republic of North Macedonia', a move that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece, which has blocked Macedonia's attempts to obtain membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece has a province called Macedonia and maintains that the name of its neighbouring country to the north constitutes a claim on Greek territory, and has therefore used their veto right when Macedonia has applied for accession to NATO and the European Union.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents believe that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's primarily Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said that he will not take part in the vote, and a boycott campaign has raised doubts as to whether the voter will make up the 50% required for the vote to be valid.
The question on the ballot was: 'Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership with acceptance of the agreement with Greece?'
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, believe that it is a price worth paying to create access to associations such as the EU and NATO for Macedonia, one of the countries that emerged as a result of the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I came today to vote on the future of the country, for young people in Macedonia, so that they can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union because it means safer lives for all of us," said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
The vote is not legally binding, but enough Members of Parliament have said that they will respect the result of the vote and put it to the vote.
The name change would require a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The State Electoral Commission said no irregularities were reported at 1:00 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16 percent compared to 34 percent in the recent 2016 general election, with 66 percent of registered voters voting.
"I voted today because of my children. We belong in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital Skopje.
Prime Minister of Macedonia Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko took part in the vote in Macedonia for a change in the country's name, which would open up to membership of NATO and the EU, in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
In front of the parliament of Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, prepared a small scene and pulled up chairs in front of tents set up by those who will boycott the vote.
"We are for NATO and the EU, but we will achieve membership with our heads up, not through the back door," said Kavadarkov.
"We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want us as Macedonia, we can turn to others like China and Russia and become part of European-Asian integration."
Prime Minister Zaev says that NATO membership would provide a much-needed investment in Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 percent.
"I believe that a large majority will vote in favour because over 80% of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO", said Zaev after casting his vote.
He said that a "yes" result would be a "safeguard of our future".
A poll released last Monday by Macedonia's Institute of Political Research indicated that between 30 and 43 percent of voters would participate in the vote – fewer than the required turnout.
Another poll made by the Macedonian television channel Telma TV indicated that 57 percent of respondents planned to vote on Sunday.
Out of these 70 percent said they would vote 'yes'.
For the vote to be valid, the turnout must be at least 50 per cent plus one vote.
