Students at Harvard take a course on getting enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University has given every undergraduate student more sleep. The purpose of the course is to counter the growing macho culture, where you study throughout the night kept up with large amounts of caffeine.
One researcher has shown that students at the world's best university often have no idea the first thing about taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at the Brigham and Women's Hospital, has done the course which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He got the idea for the course after giving a presentation on what effects sleep deprivation has on learning.
"When the presentation was finished, a girl came up to me and said, "Why am I only told now when I'm on the candidate?"
"She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is offered for the first time this year, explains how good sleeping habits can improve your academic and sporting performance as well as your overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and CEO of the university's health area, says that the university has decided to offer the course after finding out that the students were in serious sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course consists of various interactive exercises.
In one of the exercises there is a picture of a dorm room where students must click on coffee cups, curtains, running shoes and books to gain knowledge of the effects of caffeine and light, and how one's sporting performance is affected by lack of sleep and how important good sleeping habits are.
In another part of the course, participants hear about how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attacks, blood clots, depression and cancer.
Participants are encouraged to think about their daily habits by clicking on various icons on an interactive map of the campus.
"We know it will not change student behavior immediately.
But we think they have the right to know - just as one has the right to know how cigarettes affect health", adds Professor Czeisler.
The pride of taking an "allnighter" still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and increased pressure on students have led to a growing problem of sleep deprivation.
The "secret weapon" against stress, exhaustion and anxiety is good and sufficient sleep, he said – it even counteracts weight gain because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that you are starving, why they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar who studies chemical and physical biology, last year helped Professor Czeisler organize the course when he took one of his courses at his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and got him to work on making it a general course throughout the university.
He hopes that the next will be that all graduates are offered a similar course before continuing their education.
