Germany’s new warship is being postponed again
The German Navy's latest frigate should have stood ready in 2014 to replace warships from the Cold War. However, the Germans must wait at least a year yet due to technical problems and an escalating price, reports local media.
The insertion of the largest ship into the brand new Baden-Wuertemberg class of frigates, "Rheinland-Pfalz", has been postponed to the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, citing a military spokesman.
The ship should have become part of the Navy in 2014, but after delivery problems have plagued the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Wuertemberg class, which the Navy ordered back in 2007, are to replace the aging frigates of the Bremen class.
They are known to have a powerful cannon, a wide range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as stealth technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Another important feature of the latest frigates is a smaller need for maintenance: it should be possible to have frigates away from home ports for up to two years.
But the repeated delays mean that the advanced warships – which are said to make Germany appear an overseas power factor – will already be obsolete when they are deployed, Die Zeit writes.
The failed F125 frigate created headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy delivered a ship back to the shipbuilder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but German media mentioned a number of crucial "software and hardware errors" which rendered the warship useless in combat situations.
Software failures were of particular importance as the ships from the Baden-Wuertemberg class must be controlled by a crew of 120 sailors – that is only half the crew from the older Bremen frigates.
It also turned out that the ship was far too heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the fleet's ability for future updates.
The 7,000 ton heavy "Rheinland-Palatinate" is said to be twice as heavy as similar ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Besides hardware failures, the cost of the project, which includes training the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached staggering €3.1 billion ($3.6 billion), with an original price of €2.2 billion.
The problems with the latest frigates are becoming even more important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval power is shrinking.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German government's Defense Committee, earlier this year admitted that the fleet "runs out of deployable ships."
The official said the problem has grown over time because the old ships were taken out of use without being replaced.
He complained that none of the frigates from the Baden-Wuertemberg class were ready to join the Navy.
National Trust Snipers to Bats' Secret Lives
New research from an area in the Highlands of Scotland is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting.
The hope is that the finds will shed light on the behavior of the unique flying mammals and will help in the work on future conservation efforts.
The study is conducted by scientists from Scotland's National Trust and follows common bats, dwarf bats, long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at carefully selected locations in the area to record the activities of the bats during the season.
Data are also collected by staff from NTS and volunteers using handheld detectors.
In-depth analysis of the sound recordings will reveal the bat call frequencies and show which species does what.
To produce a detailed landscape picture of their behavior, a report and a map of the habitat are made.
Nature conservation advisor to NTS Rob Dewar hopes that the results reveal which areas of the habitat are most important and how they are used by the different species.
This knowledge can help determine the benefits of habitat conservation interventions such as the establishment of meadows, and how best to preserve forest areas for bats and similar species.
The number of bats in Scotland and Britain has dropped dramatically over the last 100 years.
They are threatened by buildings and urban expansion projects which affect the shipowners and restrict their habitat.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a danger, as can flytraps, chemical treatment of building materials, and attacks from pets.
Bats aren't actually blind.
But because they primarily hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes.
They use an advanced echolocation technique to find insects and fly around obstacles.
NTS, which is responsible for the preservation of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten trained experts, who often collect data, inspect nests and sometimes do rescue operations.
The organization has even made Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve at the area around Three in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight out of ten of Scotland's bat species.
The area's caretaker, David Thompson, says it is an ideal territory for them.
"Here at Three we have a very good area for bats", he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and the whole good habitat.
One there is much you don't know about bats, so the work here and elsewhere can help to understand what they need to thrive."
He stresses the importance of looking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks on properties, as the destruction of a single nest can kill up to 400 females and cubs, thus risk destroying an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or disturb them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish Project Manager for the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to lend a hand.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we have, we don't know how the populations evolve."
